    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 3 @ 2016/2017",
    "Question": {
      "content": "To charge a body positively by induction:",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "negatively charged inducing body must be used",
        "inducing charged body must be earthed",
        "inducing charged body must be connected to a source charge",
        "none of the above"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "negatively charged inducing body must be used"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<b>Charging by induction</b> is a way to charge an object without direct contact. Here’s how it works: <br><br>1. Bring a <b>negatively charged</b> rod near a neutral object. <br>2. The electrons in the neutral object are repelled, leaving one side more positive. <br>3. Ground the object (connect it to Earth), allowing electrons to escape. <br>4. Remove the ground, then the rod—the object is now positively charged. <br><br>This only works if the inducing body is negatively charged."
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electromagnetism and Electrodynamics",
      "Electrostatics",
      "Electric Induction"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 39 @ 2016/2017",
    "Question": {
      "content": "A charged insulator and an uncharged conductor:",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "Always repel",
        "Always attract",
        "No electrostatic force",
        "Attract or repel depending on charge sign"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "Always attract"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "An uncharged conductor will be <b>polarized</b> by a charged insulator, causing an attractive force regardless of the insulator’s charge sign. Thus, option (b) is correct."
    },
